          <h3 class="accent nm">History of Alpacas</h3>
          <p>Treasured by the ancient Inca civilization, alpaca's fine fleeces were reserved for Incan royalty. Alpacas provided clothing, food, fuel, and, no doubt, companionship as domesticated animals high in the altiplano of Peru, Chile and Bolivia.</p>
          <p>The alpaca was prized as a source of high quality fiber for almost 5000 years, but after the Spanish conquest of the Incas, alpacas were close to extinction. The Spaniards viewed the alpacas as a competitor for grazing lands for their sheep, and so they killed alpacas almost to the point of annihilation.</p>
          <p>The surviving Incans were driven into the highest parts of the inhospitable Andes mountains, taking their most prized alpacas with them into exile. The alpaca population survived due to their great importance to the Incan people, and their ability to tolerate extraordinarily harsh climatic conditions.</p>
          <p>Today, alpaca farming is still concentrated in the Altiplano. Today, more and more alpacas are being imported to the United States, Europe and Australia, where they benefit from modern day animal husbandry.</p>
